Description of Policy *Details of Policy *Administrative Safeguards- defines the administrative safeguards required to protect PII and sensitive company data


	 Security Officer - person responsible for implementing and monitoring the WISP
	 Security Management- requires an annual review of security and how an organization is protecting PII and sensitive company data
	 Minimal Data Collection - minimize the amount of PII collected from clients, customers and employees to only what is necessary
	 Information Access - access to PII and sensitive company data should only be granted to individuals that need the access to perform their job function
	 Employee Termination - terminated employees should be required to return all company owned assets, anyPII and sensitive company data andhave their access to data promptly removed
	 Security Training - all employees, owners, managers and contractors should receive security training
	 WISP Distribution - acopy of the WISP is to be distributed to each current employee and to each new employee on the beginning date of their employment. Employees will be required to acknowledge receipt of the WISP and are required to abide by its provisions
	 ContingencyPlanning - all systems that store PII and sensitive company data should have their data backed up. A Disaster Recovery plan should be implemented and periodically tested
	 SecurityIncident Procedures - a defined plan should be in place to respond to all suspected security incidents. Employees are required to report suspicious or unauthorized access immediately
	 Emergency Operations - procedures should be in place to define how the organizationwill respond to emergencies
	 Data Sensitivity Classification -all data that the organization stores or accesses should be categorized in terms of the sensitive nature of the information
	 Third Party Service Providers - anyservice provider thatreceives, stores, maintains, processes, or otherwise is permitted access to any file containing PII and/or sensitive company data will be required to protect PII and sensitive company data. Service providers will be required to sign service agreements that require protecting the organization's PII and sensitive data
	 Sanctions - disciplinary actions will be taken for violations of security provisions of the WISP
	 Bring Your Own Device (BYOD) - the organization may allow employees to utilize their own devices to access or store PII and sensitivedata. If allowed the BYOD policy will define the safeguard required to protect data on personally owned devices



Physical Safeguards - defines physical protections that will be implemented to protect PII and sensitive company data


	 Facility Access Controls - controls include physical security on buildings, systems that access or store PII and sensitive company data will by physically locked, employees are requiredto maintain a "clean desk"and ensure that PII and/or sensitive company data is properly secured when they are not at their desk.Visitors will be restricted from area that contain PII and sensitive company data
	 Network Security - systems that access or store PII will be isolated, encryption will be used on all portable devices that store PII and sensitive company data, all systems will up-to-date anti-malware, network firewall will be implemented, periodic vulnerability scans will be performed, system log files will be captured and retained, and critical network equipment will be stored in an environmentally safe location



Technical Safeguards - defines technical protectionthat will be implemented to protect PII and sensitivecompany data


	 Access Control - access to PII and sensitive company data will be restricted to only approved active user accounts. Employees will be assigned unique user accounts and will not share user accounts. Systems accessing or storing PII and sensitive company data will have automatic logoff procedures.
	 Computer Use - a policy that defines acceptable and unacceptable use of company computing resources. Employees will be required to sign the computer use policy
	 Data Disposal - written and electronic records containing PII and sensitive company data will be security destroyed and disposed of
	 System Activity Review - all systems that store or access PII and sensitive company data should utilize a mechanism to log and store system activity. Periodic system activity reviews should occur and identify unauthorized access to PII and sensitive company data.
	 Encryption - to the extent technically feasible all portable devices that contain PII and sensitive company data should be encrypted to protect the contents. In addition, encryption should be used when sending any PII and sensitive company data across public networks and wireless networks. Public networks include email and Internet access.
